ce:section.ce:para:
The functional groups and crystalline structure of carbon dots were shown by Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) and X-ray diffractometer (XRD). At approximately 3418 cm−1, 1732 cm−1, 1714 cm−1, 1385 cm−1, 1087 cm−1 are attributed to OH, CO, CC, CH3, and CO stretching, respectively (Fig. 1
                     c). The results of FITR indicate that there are abundant functional groups wrap around the CDs surface, which can provide more active sites (Dong et al., 2019). In addition, oxygen-containing functional groups can contribute to forming stable solid electrolyte interface (SEI) and reduce electrode side reactions (Hou et al., 2015). XRD results indicate that the obtained CDs is an amorphous carbon phase with a polymer-carbon hybrid structure (a wide peak at about 20°) (Fig. 1
                     d). The microstructure of CDs is also observed by transmission electron microscope (TEM) (
                        Fig. S2
                     ). It can be indicated from the image that the size of CDs is about 2 ∼ 3 nm and the distribution is uniform (
                        Fig. S3
                     ), which is beneficial for achieving uniform deposition of K metal anode as reported in the previous literature (Li et al., 2021). It was found that the electrolyte with CDs was yellowish green when it was exposed to UV lamp, and the fluorescence emission spectra of CDs collected also indicate that the CDs have fluorescence and have good dispersion in the electrolyte (
                        Fig. S4
                     ) (Hou et al., 2017; Tu et al., 2023).

Moreover, CDs also can be used as the nucleation site of K+, thus significantly reducing the energy barrier of nucleation process (Li et al., 2021). As shown in Fig. 2 e and f, the nucleation overpotential of the cells containing CDs was −0.04 V, while the nucleation overpotential of cells without CDs was −0.07 V (Pei et al., 2017; Wang, 2020). The long cycle testing further proves this point, for the cell with CDs, which can cycle stability over 1400 h, while the cells without CDs presented shorted out only after 120 h (Fig. 2g). As discussed above, the addition of CDs provides more active sites that adsorb potassium ions and guide uniform deposition (Hou et al., 2017). However, we should note that the content of additives is crucial, small amount of CDs don’t provide sufficient nucleation sites to facilitate K+ deposition and excessive CDs will increase the viscosity of the electrolyte and affect the battery performance (
Fig. S6
). The cycling stability test at 0.2 mA cm−2 also proved that the CDs additive can effectively regulate the deposition behavior of K metal anode and achieve uniform and stable deposition-dissolution ( Fig. S7 ).
